SIMPLE: pertain
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pertain
<hw>Per*tain"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Pertained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Pertaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>partenen</ets>, OF. <ets>partenir</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>pertinere</ets> to stretch out, reach, pertain; <ets>per +
tenere</ets> to hold, keep. See <er>Per-</er>, and <er>Tenable</er>, and
cf. <er>Appertain</er>, <er>Pertinent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
belong; to have connection with, or dependence on, something, as an
appurtenance, attribute, etc.; to appertain; <as>as, saltness
<ex>pertains</ex> to the ocean; flowers <ex>pertain</ex> to plant
life.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men hate those who affect that honor by ambition which
<qex>pertaineth</qex> not to them.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have relation or reference to
something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These words <qex>pertain</qex> unto us at this time as they
<qex>pertained</qex> to them at their time.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perterebration</ent>⟦br⟧
